<div id="introduction" class="section level1">
<h1>Introduction</h1>
<div id="lidar-height-diversity-index-lhdi" class="section level2">
<h2>Lidar Height Diversity Index (LHDI)</h2>
<p>The LHDI quantifies the diversity of heights or elevations in a
specific area covered by the Lidar data. It is calculated by analyzing
the proportion of returns (measured laser pulses) falling within
different canopy height intervals <span class="math inline">\(h\)</span>. The index measures the complexity and
vertical variability of vegetation within the surveyed region. A higher
LHDI value indicates greater structural diversity, suggesting a more
complex forest canopy with vegetation at various height levels.</p>
<p>The formula to calculate LHDI is: <span class="math display">\[ LHDI
= -\sum (p_h \times \ln(p_h)) \]</span></p>
<p>where: <span class="math inline">\(p_h\)</span> is the proportion of
returns in the defined height interval <span class="math inline">\(h\)</span>, and the summation <span class="math inline">\(\sum\)</span> is performed across all height
intervals.</p>
</div>
<div id="lidar-height-evenness-index-lhei" class="section level2">
<h2>Lidar Height Evenness Index (LHEI)</h2>
<p>The LHEI is related to the LHDI and provides a measure of the
evenness or uniformity of vegetation heights in the surveyed area. It is
calculated by dividing the LHDI by the natural logarithm of the
proportion of returns in the defined height interval <span class="math inline">\(h\)</span>. The LHEI helps to assess how evenly
distributed vegetation is across different height intervals.</p>
<p>The formula to calculate LHEI is: <span class="math display">\[ LHEI
= \frac{LHDI}{\ln(p_h)} \]</span></p>
<p>where: <br> In both cases <span class="math inline">\(p\)</span> is
the proportion of returns in the defined height interval <span class="math inline">\(h\)</span> in each bin.</p>
<p>For further information please revise:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Listopad, C. M. C. S., R. E. Masters, J. Drake, J. Weishampel,
&amp; C. Branquinho. <strong>Structural diversity indices based on
airborne LiDAR as ecological indicators for managing highly dynamic
landscapes</strong>. <em>Ecological Indicators</em> 57 (2015). <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ecolind.2015.04.017">doi.org/10.1016/j.ecolind.2015.04.017</a></p></li>
<li><p>Gelabert, P., A. L. Montealegre, M. T. Lamelas, &amp; D. Domingo.
<strong>Forest structural diversity characterization in Mediterranean
landscapes affected by fires using Airborne Laser Scanning
data</strong>. <em>GIScience &amp; Remote Sensing</em> 57, 4 (2020). <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/15481603.2020.1738060.">doi.org/10.1080/15481603.2020.1738060.</a></p></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
